	     <tr><td id=headerrow colspan=2 class=mform valign=top><a name=>&nbsp;</a><a id=sj href=>Ranger Strategy.</a> <a id=fs8 href=#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a>
	     <br clear=all><small>Posted @ Mon, Jul 16th 8:24 PM 2001</small></td></tr>
	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=76316><span id= >BarahirMT</span></a><br><span id=notbold>6 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good [4.20]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>OK, thought I would at least post something of value (I hope).&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><br>I've heard all the comments on how "Rangers are the worst class", how we don't get the HP to go toe-to-toe with the mobs like Warriors do, we don't get feign death like the monks, do, etc. and so forth.  Well, 51 levels later, nearly 52, this is my outlook on the class I chose to pursue.  I've had times where I couldn't find a group for days, other times where I could walk into a zone and get tells for invites.  Well, here's what I think;<br><br>1.  Rangers get options;  Rangers can solo at any level and do it well.  Can't find a group?  Excellent experience solo, whether it's goblins in ButcherBlock or Wyverns in Cobalt Scar, you can bet a ranger can always single kite a mob.  A Ranger can solo a mob at a far earlier level than a Warrior (a glaring fact which makes Warriors group-oriented playes).  Rangers also heal, buff, and get that ever-popular SoW at 30, and we all know how much SoW is appreciated by ALL levels (even those who wear J-Boots would like a SoW).  Rangers are also excellent group players and damage dealers.  What's that you say?  Rangers deal damage?  Yes we do and we do it well.  We can melee like the warriors and the added damage spells (dot's, dd) add to the rangers already impressive arsenal of skills.  Rangers get all the combat skills of the warriors (save bash, no bashing for us).  Some of these skills are capped in later levels (like kick) but point for point Rangers, especially after 49 and on, can out-damage a Warrior with the addition of those spells the tanks don't get.  Didn't know that, did you.  Only Monks and Rogues can beat the Rangers for melee damage output.  <br><br>2.  Rangers Snare - This is a critical function, especially in the high-level game (We also get Ensnare at 51, upgrade of standard snare).  Why is that?  Ask any member in a group who has had a mob run away from them only to have it aggro other mobs and train them back.  You can have a group of 3 of the best Warriors for your level but if no one snares, then the mob can run.  Druids can snare as well, however, Snare is a major taunt to a mob and focuses aggro on the snaring party.  A Druid has a smaller hit point reserve and cannot take the punishment like the Rangers.  At high levels, Rangers even get a spell that reduces aggro (Jolt).  And the upper levels are all about aggro control.  <br><br>3. Tracking - Yes, it's very obvious we can track.  So can the druids and the bards.  However, Rangers' tracking is not capped.  Furthermore, our tracking lists can be sorted or filtered by distance and level of mob (an ability only the Rangers get).  A 51 Druid still has a tracking ability of 125.  A 51 Ranger will have the tracking ability of 200 or greater.  Next time you're in South Karana, who would you rather track Quillmane for you?  Think on that.<br><br>4.  Archery - Rangers are the best archers in the game.  Period.  Why is that important?  Ranger tactic is Snare, Root and Shoot.  Snare the target, pull it back to a safe area, Root it so it doesn't go anywhere, and Shoot it using that archery ability and alternate spell casts in there.  Ok, big deal, so they can shoot arrows.  Oh, did I mention the discipline of double damage on each bowshot at 51 and above (only if the mob is not rooted or engaging another melee) and the Trueshot Discipline at 55.  Depending on the bow used, at level 55 and above a Ranger can stand back and shoot with these disciplines and inflict damage on the average of 300-500 pts each shot, with critical hits of up to 1100 pts. each (Efreeti bow will allow this, depending on the arrows used as well).  Not to mention certain bows have proc's and effects as well.  My personal best critical hit thus far has been 181 pts (using a Runed Oak Bow and Class 5 Ceramic shaft/vane hook point arrows).  I consistently hit 40-80 pts. damage depending on the fight.  Sometimes I miss, but not often.  And tagging mobs in tandem with a monk requires some distance, which you get with the arrows/bow you use.  Better start working on that Fletching skill. <br><br>5. Unique spells - Certain classes get unique spells.  Rangers have theirs (lower levels get Feet Like Cat/Agility, upper levels get Call of Earth/Damage Shield and Armor Class buff, to name a few).  Not to mention Call of Flame, Jolt, etc.  Plus, Rangers get to share in some of the Druid spell use (albeit at later levels), like Sow (30), Wolf Form (49), etc.  Level 25-29 has to be the hardest levels for a Ranger, getting into groups can be trying at times because some other classes don't quite understand the abilities a ranger can bring to the group.  When you hit level 30, all that changes, because now you can SoW (which you will be doing the rest of your days, I don't even travel without SoW on anymore).  <br><br>6. Utility - Rangers can do many of the things another melee can and some things better.  At 30 and above, you now have the ability to really pull outdoor mobs better than most other folks.  3 spells will enable you to do this effectively;  SoW, Snare, and Harmony.  Harmony?  It's an aggro-range reducing spell which allows you to pick out certain mobs from a cluster of them (the avocets at the bottom of the bird ramp in SK, for example, or Pickclaws in the Warrior Room in Highpass - yes, out door spells work in Highkeep).  Rather than having to face an on-rush of many mobs, a Ranger can Harmony, pick off one with a bow shot, snare them, then drag them back to the group to be dealt with.  If you're pulling mobs indoors, stick with the Monks and the SK's, but for real outdoor pulling, go with the Rangers.  You won't be disappointed.  <br><br>7. Raids - Oh, ok, so you are starting to raid the Planes and you seem to not be getting all the invites the "critical classes" get (critical like Clerics, Enchanters, Monks, and Warriors).  Good news is most Planar Raids take a wide variety of talents and skills and you fit two of them as a Ranger (snaring and melee damage).  Two places Rangers excel at right off the bat are Fear and Plane of Growth.  PoG?  What? That's like so wrong, you say!  There's nothing to kill up on PoG for us!  True, but there's not a Raid Leader around who doesn't appreciate a good tracker/scout who can wander PoG unmolested and call out mobs.  A raid leader with a Ranger or 2 in PoG will remember those Rangers and ask them to other raids because that shows some spirit.  Think of it, you run around calling mobs all day for no armor and no loot drops for somebody else.  Raid Leaders appreciate that and you will be asked on others as a result of it.   And Fear is an outdoor zone, all of your spells come into play.  You can tag and kite mobs there too.  And deal damage.  And Snare (see above).  <br><br>8. Supreme hunters - Rangers can take on the ever-fearsome griffons (and Grimfeather) and other such animals with Panic Animal Spell.  Snare/Fear/Dot/Melee is your trick.  Any animals will succumb to this and it will have similar level warriors green with envy when they see you soloing that Griff.  <br><br>Now, does this little treatise here mean that other classes are not as good?  Not by any means.  Each character has it's specific talents and abilities that make them special in group situations.  A Warrior takes punishment better than any other character.  That's his/her job.  A Monk deals damage and can take punishment like a tank but can also pull mobs other classes couldn't survive.  A Paladin specializes in fighting undead (best melee's in the game for that) and they have that all-important stun.  A Shadowknight has that wicked Harmtouch ability and can certainly dole out damage too.  Bards have mana-free songs and can track corpses, move parties faster than sow, and mez mobs (cool, huh).  And the caster classes all specialize in certain things that make grouping very desireable with them (clerics for heals, Necros for dot's, Shamen for best buffs all around, 'Chanters for crowd control, Wizards for nukes, Mages for those wonderful pets, etc.)  The list goes on.  And Rangers belong in a group just like any other class.  <br><br>It boils down to this;  any class, played well, can contribute to a group.  Rangers have certain skills that make them highly desirable.  Play to those skills and you shouldn't have any trouble finding a group or surviving that solo encounter.  <br><br>I enjoy my ranger immensely.  And I have started playing other classes just to get a feel for their side.  And when I do, I miss 2 things most of all;  Tracking and SoW.  How the other classes survive so long without the 2 is sometimes a wonder to me.  <br><br>Enjoy and play away.  <br></p>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
